{
  "card_id": "volume",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Volume",
  "aliases": [
    "volume bars",
    "Volume Bars"
  ],
  "school": "Volume Analysis",
  "definition": "Volume is the number of shares, contracts, or units traded during a given period, typically per candle. It appears as histogram bars below price charts, with bar height indicating total traded quantity. Higher volume signals greater market participation and agreement on price validity, confirming breakouts and trend strength.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Each price candle has a corresponding volume bar below the chart; taller bars indicate higher trading activity.",
    "Identify volume spikes by comparing the current bar's height to preceding bars; a spike is distinctly larger (often at least three times the average size of recent bars).",
    "A breakout above resistance or below support is confirmed when the breakout candle exhibits a volume spike, indicating strong participation.",
    "In an established trend, rising volume validates trend strength; declining volume may signal weakening momentum and potential reversal.",
    "Use volume profile to visualize traded volume at each price level, identifying high-volume nodes as areas of concentrated order flow.",
    "Apply a moving average to volume (e.g., 14-period) to smooth fluctuations and detect when volume is significantly above or below its average.",
    "Some chart platforms color volume bars green (buyer-dominated) or red (seller-dominated) for the period."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Volume is a confirmation tool that validates price moves. Breakouts accompanied by high volume signal strong market participation and are more likely to sustain. Declining volume during a trend warns of weakening momentum and potential reversal. Traders should enter only on breakouts with significant volume to avoid false signals, improving entry timing and confidence.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Ignoring volume when assessing breakout validity, leading to false signals because breakouts on low volume are more likely to fail.",
    "Assuming all large volume bars are bullish without considering context; volume only shows participation, not direction.",
    "Mistaking any above-average volume for a valid breakout signal without requiring a spike significantly larger (e.g., three times) than previous bars."
  ],
